To anyone interested in this subject:

This exchange of messages addresses the speed of convergence of the 
cstr, but a closely related subject is the fact that there is a rich 
literature of time-dependent stirred reactor experiments that can be 
simulated with lots of interesting phenomena.  This includes 
time-dependent cool flames for lower temperature hydrocarbons, with 
many outstanding experiments from Pier-Giorgio Lignola and others, as 
well as higher temperature time-dependent, periodic ignition 
experiments from Phil Malte&#39;s group at U Washington.  There are lot 
more from others as well.

Both Chemkin and HCT were adapted quite a long time ago to solve the 
numerical problem that Ulf suggests, not so much to accelerate 
solution of the steady-state problem as to address time-dependent 
stirred reactor applications.  HCT solves the time-independent 
problem as the long-time, steady solution of the time-dependent 
problem, just as it solves the steady flame propagation problem as 
the long-time solution of the unsteady problem.  In principle, he 
could use the flame code and ask for only one spatial zone, with 
specified input fluxes of reactant concentrations and a zero pressure 
gradient as the boundary conditions at the other boundary.

I don&#39;t know if there is any documentation of the Chemkin version of 
this problem, and as usual, no documentation exists for the HCT 
implementatio except in the half-dozen or so papers we have written 
using the feature.

Charlie Westbrook





